'''Irish twins''' is a derogatory term that refers to siblings born 9 to 12 months apart - usually in the same calendar year, or who are in the same grade in school.  Similarly, '''Irish triplets''' means three children in three years.  

It references the large families of [[Irish Catholic]]s who did not use birth control (and thus had many children in quick succession).  

As a slur, it has a triple meaning, that the Irish were more likely to have kids one after the other because of the Catholic Church's ban on birth control, less likely to restrain themselves from procreating, and unable to understand the proper meaning of the terms "twins" and "triplets."

The use of "Irish" as a derogatory prefix dates to when the Irish immigrated in large numbers to North America, and the Irish became the targets of discrimination.  Other terms from that time are [[Irish confetti]], [[Irish kiss]] and [[Irish banjo]].

